\significancestatement{We build a mortality model that not only integrates intra and inter-specific variation but also, simultaneously estimates the two fundamental hazards faced by plants -- Death due to low growth rates and death independent of growth -- and how a species' light demand, maximum dbh and wood density affect each. We parameterize this model using over 400,000 observed survival records collected over a 15-year period from more than 180,000 individuals across 203 species. We show that growth-dependent hazards are a significant contributor to tree mortality at Barro Colorado Island. Moreover, we show that species traits -- wood density, maximum dbh and light demand -- all affect tree mortality rates but ultimately only account for a small fraction of the total variability among species.}


