Tree death is a key process driving population dynamics, nutrient cycling, and evolution within plant communities. While the risk of death varies among forests and from year-to-year \cite{vanMantgem:2009bi}, trees growing within the same forest also vary remarkably in realised risk of death\cite{Condit:2006}. In tropical forests, annual mortality can differ 20-60 fold among populations of coexisting species \cite{Condit:2006}. These differences reflect differences in the way trees from different species are constructed and function, and arise via a coordinated axis of life-history variation, in which individuals from species with higher potential-growth rates also experience higher mortality \cite{Wright:2010fl}. At the same time, the risk of death varies widely within species, with those individuals growing slower or sitting lower in the light spectrum at greater risk \cite{Kobe:1995tw, Wyckoff:2000un, Vieilledent:2010fv}. While these inter- and intra-specific patterns of mortality are widely recognised, they show conflicting relationships with tree growth rate (increasing with growth rate across species, decreasing with growth rate within species), making it difficult to integrate both sources of variation into a predictive model.

In this article we outline a new approach for predicting mortality among individuals within a forest, incorporating both inter and intra-specific variation in risk. Our approach builds on the notion that the total risk of death at any time is the additive effect of at least two, largely independent risks \cite{Keane:2001db}. Although plants die because of many causes, these broadly fall into two main categories \cite{Keane:2001db, McDowell:2011dr}. The first are growth-independent hazards, which cause death irrespective of the tree's current growth rate, and may include windfall, fire, and certain types of pathogen or herbivore attack. These hazards are assumed to occur at some average rate (Fig 1a, left). The second are growth-dependent hazards, which cause slower growing plants within each species to die at a faster rate, presumably because inferior carbon budgets make them unable to tolerate diverse stresses \cite{Kobe:1995tw, Hawkes:2000ib, Keane:2001db}. Many empirical studies suggest an exponential decline in risk with increased growth rate, $X_i(t)$ \cite{Kobe:1995tw, Wyckoff:2000un, Vieilledent:2010fv} (Fig 1a, centre). An individual's total risk of dying is then the sum of these two (Fig 1a, right). Biologically, the additive model implies that even fast-growing individuals experience some risk of death.

While already applied in some vegetation models \cite{Moorcroft:2001ws}, the additive hazards model has not previously been applied in empirical studies. Moreover, we note that the underlying mathematical structure of statistical methods used in most previous empirical studies imply responses similar to either the left or centre panels of Fig 1a (see SI Appendix S1). In particular, commonly used methods -- including exponential models \cite{Kobe:1995tw, Wyckoff:2000un}, logistic regression \cite{Ruger:2011cv}, generalized linear models \cite{Visser_functional_2016}, and Cox proportional-hazard models \cite{Neumann_climate_2017} -- handle covariates in a manner that allows predicted risk to decline to zero for fast growing individuals (as in Fig 1a centre; SI Appendix S1). These methods may therefore fail to capture the full range of variation observed within and among species.

\section*{An additive hazards models with species effects}

In forests, mortality rates are usually estimated from census data, where the size and fate of individual trees is recorded at successive time points \cite{Anderson-Teixeira-2015a} (Fig 1b). The size and status of individuals at each census -- alive vs. dead -- can then be used to estimate $\lambda_i(t)$, a continuous, latent, mortality (or `hazard`) rate for all individuals in group $i$ at time $t$. Using this approach, the probability an individual dies between times $t_1$ and $t_2$ results from the cumulative hazard they are exposed to between censuses\cite{Kleinbaum:2012tn}:
\begin{equation} \label{eq:mortality_model}
p_{i,t_1\rightarrow t_2} = 1 - \exp\left(- \int_{t_1}^{t_2} \lambda_i(t) {\rm d}t\right),
\end{equation}
The observed survival outcome $S_{i, t_1\rightarrow t_2}$ (0 = alive, 1 = died) is then modelled as a binary draw. The challenge is then to estimate an appropriate form for the hazard rate, $\lambda_i(t)$. 

Here we propose the following hazard function, incorporating individual-, species-, and temporal effects:
\begin{equation} \label{eq:model}
\lambda_{i}(t) = \bigg(\overbrace{\gamma_{s}}^{\text{Growth independent}} + \overbrace{\alpha_{s} \, \textrm{e}^{-\beta_{s} \, X_{s,i}(t)}}^{\text{Growth dependent}}\bigg) \times \overbrace{\delta_{t}}^{\text{Census}}.
\end{equation}
Eq. \ref{eq:model} allows for additive growth-dependent and growth-independent effects, includes a negative exponential effect of individual's growth rate (our measure of carbon budget), allows the overall mortality rate to vary among censuses via the random effect $\delta_{t}$, while also allowing species-level differences in the shape of $\lambda_i(t)$ via the parameters $\alpha_s$, $\beta_s$ and $\gamma_s$. The species-level parameters are in turn modelled as random effects, drawn from  an overall distribution.

