\section*{Case study: Tropical forest at Barro Colorado Island}

To illustrate the proposed mortality model, we assess it's ability to predict the survival status of \Sexpr{n_inds(BCI_training_full)} individual trees from containing \Sexpr{n_spp(BCI_training_full)}  species, recorded over three 5-year census periods at Barro Colorado Island (BCI), Panama. Mortality rates are known to vary widely among species, and also vary within species in response to light levels and growth rates \cite{Condit:2006, Wright:2010fl, Ruger:2011cv}. Applying the additive model, we: i) estimate growth-dependent and growth-independent effects from long-term census data, ii) estimate species-level differences in these effects, and iii) assess how well strength species-level differences is predicted from three key traits, previously shown to correlate with mortality. Here we consider three species traits thought to drive inter-specific variation in mortality: wood density, light demand, and maximum dbh \cite{king:2006va, Kraft:2010kq, Wright:2010fl, Ruger:2011cv}. Overall, these traits only show weak correlation (r$^2$ \textless 0.13) and thus provide relatively independent measures of a species ecological strategy (SI Appendix, Fig. S6).

Our analysis proceeds in a series of stages, in which we compare the predictive power of alternative models, differing in either structure or covariates included. We used 10-fold cross-validation to evaluate the skill of different models in their ability to predict outcomes in novel data (i.e. not used in model fitting), using a likelihood-based penalty for incorrect prediction (Fig. \ref{fig1}C-D; see Methods) \cite{Hooten:2015, Stone:1997tg}. n total \Sexpr{n_obs(BCI_training_full)} observations were used to fit these models. Evaluating models in this way is computationally expensive, making it impossible to run all possible model formulations. We therefore fit models across six iterative stages of model development, described below, gradually building up in complexity, comparing their predictive skill on new data. We then use the final model to assess how traits align with different effects and quantify the contributions of different effects on overall model performance. 

