\subsection*{Stage 1: Mortality over time}
We first assess whether average mortality rates varied among the three censuses, and thus, whether a census effect is required in Eq \ref{eq:model}. We compared a model with a constant mortality rate, $\gamma$, to a model where the constant is scaled by a census effect, $\gamma\delta_{t}$. Examining the three 5-year census intervals, we found average mortality rates declining over time: with the highest proportion of death occurring from 1995\textendash 2000 (\Sexpr{prop_deaths(BCI_training_full, 1)}\%) followed by 2000\textendash 2005 (\Sexpr{prop_deaths(BCI_training_full, 2)}\%) and 2005\textendash 2010 (\Sexpr{prop_deaths(BCI_training_full, 3)}\%). Consequently, we observed a small increase in predictive skill when a census effect was included (Fig. \ref{fig2}).

\subsection*{Stage 2: Hazard functions}
Second, we assessed the predictive performance of three alternative hazard functions (Fig. \ref{fig1}A). The simplest form (Fig. \ref{fig1}A, left) assumes a constant hazard. The second form (Fig. \ref{fig1}A, middle) assumes the risk of dying declines towards an asymptote of zero as growth, and thus carbon budget, increases. The third "additive" model (Fig. \ref{fig1}BA right) is the sum of the previous two. In doing this, we also investigated which growth measure (stem diameter, stem area increment) more skilfully predicts growth-dependent mortality. Comparing the three hazard functions, the additive function significantly outperformed both the baseline and growth-dependent only hazard functions (Fig. \ref{fig2}). Moreover, we found that predictive skill was higher when using stem diameter growth relative to stem-area growth (Fig. \ref{fig2}).

\subsection*{Stages 3-5: Species traits}

In the following 3 stages stages, we compare the most predictive hazard function and growth rate measure from stage 2 (additive model using dbh growth rate) and ask how addition of 1, 2 and 3 species-level traits improves model performance. Specifically, we introduce effects of the traits maximum dbh ($\psi$), light demand ($\upsilon$) and wood density ($\rho$) on the parameters $\alpha$, $\beta$ and $\gamma$ in Eq. \ref{eq:model}, at first one at a time (stage 3), then in 2-trait (stage 4) and 3-trait (stage 5) combinations. In general we found that including trait effects on these parameters decreased logarithmic loss, and thus, increased predictive accuracy (Fig.~\ref{fig2}). Moreover, we found that incorporating the effect of all three traits on these parameters resulted in higher predictive capacity relative to models that only incorporated one or two of the traits.

\subsection*{Stages 6: Species random effects}

Lastly, we fit a model that included a species random effect on each parameter. This allowed us to 1) examine the maximum predictive capacity when accounting for species differences; and 2) provides a relative indication on how much of the total species variation is captured by the three traits. We found that the increase in predictive accuracy afforded by traits (stage 5) was small relative to including species random effects on each parameter, which account for unexplained species differences, signifying that substantial inter-specific variation in mortality rates remains unexplained (Fig. \ref{fig2} Stage 6).

\subsection*{Parameter importance and trait effects}

In order to examine how species differed in hazards functions and to understand the effects of species traits, we used the entire dataset to fit final model containing all three species traits and a species random effect (which captures inter-specific variation that unexplained by traits) on each of $\alpha$, $\beta$ and $\gamma$. We found that each trait influenced tree mortality in different ways (Fig. \ref{fig3}-\ref{fig4}). Specifically, we found that light demanding species were more susceptible to low growth rates (i.e. higher $\alpha$), had higher growth-independent hazards (i.e. higher $\gamma$) and exhibited shallower declines in growth-dependent hazards with increasing growth rates (i.e. lower $\beta$). By contrast, we found that wood density had significant impacts on $\alpha$ and $\gamma$, such that species with high wood density were less susceptible to low growth rates and had lower growth-independent hazards. Species' maximum dbh only had significant effects on $\gamma$, whereby species that can achieve larger dbh exhibited lower growth-independent hazards. 

